{{Definition
|Entry=Inference
|Description=The detailed knowledge about a schema or frame that constitutes the internal logic of that schema or frame by which we reason about that schema or frame; inferences fall out from our understanding of a schema or frame given the constraints on that schema or frame. Traditionally, inference and entailment are synonymous. In the Wiki, inference is kept to refer to the internal logic of a schema or frame, while entailment is used to refer to the corresponding logic in the target domain in a metaphoric mapping.
|Applies to=Schema
|Entered by=Elise,
}}

{{Definition
|Entry=Inference
|Description=The detailed knowledge about a schema or frame that constitutes the internal logic of that schema or frame by which we reason about that schema or frame; inferences fall out from our understanding of a schema or frame given the constraints on that schema or frame. Traditionally, inference and entailment are synonymous. In the Wiki, inference is kept to refer to the internal logic of a schema or frame, while entailment is used to refer to the corresponding logic in the target domain in a metaphoric mapping.
